WEBVTT

00:03.567 --> 00:05.300
Good morning, everyone.

00:05.302 --> 00:06.801
Camera three,
you have the commissioner.

00:06.803 --> 00:08.203
Camera two, you have Norah.

00:08.205 --> 00:10.338
Camera one,
you'll get the D.A.

00:10.340 --> 00:14.042
Stand by to cue Norah
in seven, six...

00:14.044 --> 00:17.212
...five, four, three...

00:17.214 --> 00:19.181
...two, one.

00:19.183 --> 00:20.482
Welcome back.

00:20.484 --> 00:22.050
Joining us this morning
are two of the men

00:22.052 --> 00:24.186
most responsible for
the safety and welfare

00:24.188 --> 00:25.720
of the great city we call home:

00:25.722 --> 00:28.423
veteran New York City Police
Commissioner Frank Reagan...

00:28.425 --> 00:30.425
Thank you, Norah.
A pleasure to be here.

00:30.427 --> 00:32.394
...and the newly
appointed interim

00:32.396 --> 00:34.062
Manhattan District Attorney,
Robert McCoy.

00:34.064 --> 00:34.996
Welcome.

00:34.998 --> 00:36.998
Thank you, Norah.
Commissioner,

00:37.000 --> 00:39.167
under your watch,
this city has been enjoying

00:39.169 --> 00:41.169
a significant
reduction in crime

00:41.171 --> 00:42.404
in the last
two years.

00:42.406 --> 00:43.638
There are some people
that are saying

00:43.640 --> 00:47.075
this is now the "safest
big city in America."

00:47.077 --> 00:48.443
What do you
attribute that to?

00:48.445 --> 00:50.478
Well, Norah, it's been

00:50.480 --> 00:52.881
a pretty straightforward
approach.

00:52.883 --> 00:55.250
More trained officers
in the high-crime areas,

00:55.252 --> 00:57.285
making solid arrests,
and, of course,

00:57.287 --> 00:58.620
following cases

00:58.622 --> 00:59.988
through to their
conclusion.

00:59.990 --> 01:02.691
But it certainly
has been a successful strategy.

01:02.693 --> 01:04.325
Thank you, Norah.
Mm-hmm.

01:04.328 --> 01:05.727
Thank you very much.

01:05.729 --> 01:07.529
But there's always
room for improvement.

01:07.531 --> 01:10.298
What do you mean, Mr. McCoy?
If you drill down

01:10.300 --> 01:13.501
on the numbers, you can see that
we devote far too many resources

01:13.503 --> 01:16.371
to so-called quality-of-life
crimes. I think those resources

01:16.373 --> 01:19.541
could be put to better use
to further reduce the incidents

01:19.543 --> 01:21.910
of violent
and destructive felonies.

01:21.912 --> 01:24.512
Well, Norah,
quality-of-life crimes lead

01:24.514 --> 01:27.249
to the breakdown of communities,
which lead

01:27.251 --> 01:29.684
to more of the exact kind
of crimes you're talking about.

01:29.686 --> 01:30.852
With all due respect,

01:30.854 --> 01:33.688
I don't think the
facts bear that out.

01:33.690 --> 01:36.124
They do if you know
how to read them.

01:37.327 --> 01:38.460
Well, Mr. McCoy,

01:38.462 --> 01:40.495
what kind of changes
are you gonna be making?

01:40.497 --> 01:42.063
Well, for example,
I'm instructing

01:42.065 --> 01:43.098
my assistant district attorneys

01:43.100 --> 01:44.833
that we are no longer
going to prosecute

01:44.835 --> 01:48.803
petty marijuana possession
charges.

01:48.805 --> 01:52.173
That would be a rookie mistake
of the first stripe.

01:52.175 --> 01:54.442
Commissioner,
I may have been born yesterday,

01:54.444 --> 01:57.412
but I stayed up late studying.

01:57.414 --> 02:00.448
So let me get this
straight, you're not gonna

02:00.450 --> 02:03.885
prosecute crimes,
even after police make arrests?

02:03.887 --> 02:06.554
I would look for Commissioner
Reagan's cooperation in setting

02:06.556 --> 02:08.556
new guidelines
for his officers, yes.

02:08.558 --> 02:10.658
Well, Commissioner,
your response on that.

02:10.661 --> 02:15.297
I would say to the interim D.A.
that's a fool's errand.

02:15.299 --> 02:17.465
Mom, hurry up!

02:17.467 --> 02:19.200
What?

02:19.202 --> 02:21.403
Your boss is
going after Grandpa big-time.

02:21.405 --> 02:23.972
It's a matter of
where to best allocate

02:23.974 --> 02:24.906
energy and resources.

02:24.908 --> 02:26.508
Commissioner.

02:26.510 --> 02:31.713
Look, I did not come here
to debate policy,

02:31.715 --> 02:33.748
and there are
certainly guidelines

02:33.750 --> 02:35.717
which must be followed in order

02:35.719 --> 02:38.920
to change laws, which is
what we're talking about here.

02:38.922 --> 02:39.888
I'm not changing laws.
You're talking

02:39.890 --> 02:41.823
about selectively
enforcing them,

02:41.825 --> 02:43.291
which is effectively
the same thing.

02:43.293 --> 02:45.627
And you disagree
with that.

02:45.629 --> 02:48.129
Of course I do.

02:48.131 --> 02:49.597
You guys came loaded for this.

02:49.599 --> 02:52.534
Garrett, he is merely
announcing new policy.

02:52.536 --> 02:54.536
On national TV
with no forewarning?

02:54.538 --> 02:57.739
That's not an announcement;
that's an ambush.

02:58.942 --> 03:02.510
Commissioner?

03:02.512 --> 03:05.580
Okay. We will leave it there.

03:05.582 --> 03:07.282
Thank you, gentlemen.

03:07.284 --> 03:09.250
To be continued.

03:09.252 --> 03:10.819
Condron, that's two strikes.

03:10.821 --> 03:13.021
One more, the judge is gonna
turn this leather jacket

03:13.023 --> 03:15.190
into an orange jumpsuit.

03:19.763 --> 03:21.730
Where's my partner?

03:21.732 --> 03:23.365
You're looking at her.

03:23.367 --> 03:25.133
What?
I make it my business

03:25.135 --> 03:29.738
to partner at least one tour
with every one of my detectives.

03:29.740 --> 03:31.673
Your detectives?
So I can get to know them

03:31.675 --> 03:33.775
on a deeper level.

03:33.777 --> 03:35.910
Baez.

03:35.912 --> 03:39.214
Look, there's really
nothing more to me.

03:39.216 --> 03:41.449
What you see is what you get,
so how 'bout we take a pass?

03:41.451 --> 03:43.852
Detective Reagan and I will be
in the field.

03:43.854 --> 03:45.820
If anything comes up,
you can get me on my cell phone.

03:45.822 --> 03:46.855
Sure.

03:46.857 --> 03:48.390
No problem.

03:48.392 --> 03:50.258
Let's go, Reagan.

03:51.995 --> 03:55.063
This ought to be fun.

03:58.969 --> 04:01.803
This came in as a 10-10?

04:01.805 --> 04:03.571
Yeah, possible crime.

04:03.573 --> 04:05.573
Probably turn out
to be nothing.

04:05.575 --> 04:07.842
"Sorry, I can't do this
anymore..."

04:07.844 --> 04:08.877
Huh?!

04:08.879 --> 04:10.545
What?

04:10.547 --> 04:12.113
Pete just broke up with me.

04:12.115 --> 04:13.348
Oh, the stockbroker?

04:13.350 --> 04:15.049
No, the start-up guy.

04:15.051 --> 04:16.885
I didn't think you
were that into him.

04:16.887 --> 04:18.685
That's not the point.

04:18.688 --> 04:20.288
What is?

04:20.290 --> 04:21.856
He says I'm demanding.
Can you believe that?

04:21.858 --> 04:24.025
Do you think
I'm demanding?

04:26.963 --> 04:29.330
Think we can rule out
a possible crime.

04:29.332 --> 04:31.666
My God.

